article.headline: Jocelyn's 25 points help South Carolina improve to 8-0
article.linkText: Poor shooting dooms Cajuns against No. 19 Gamecocks
article.story:
COLUMBIA, S.C. -- Louisiana-Lafayette coach J. Kelley Hall
had one question for his players at halftime.

	   "How many of you hit a two-point field goal?'' he asked.
"Raise your hand.''

	   None went up. That's what happens when you shoot 2-of-22 (9.1
percent) in the opening period and miss your first 16 two-point
tries as the Rajun Cajuns did in a 70-41 loss to (No. 19 ESPN/USA Today, No. 18 AP) South
Carolina on Wednesday night.

	   "I've never been through anything like it,'' he said.

	   Few coaches have.

	   "Our team knew exactly what they were going to see and they
went out and executed the defensive game plan very well,'' South
Carolina coach Susan Walvius said.

	   Jocelyn scored 25 points -- three fewer than her average -- as the
Gamecocks (8-0) continued on their best start since going 9-0 in
1988-89. But it was the defensive effort that carried them in this
one.

	   Everything went South Carolina's way in the first half.

	   "We came out scared and not ready to play,'' Louisiana
Lafayette's Sarah Richey said. "It was sickening.''

	   South Carolina guard Kelly Morrone hit her first four
3-pointers, Penn continually beat the Rajun' Cajuns down the court
for easy baskets on the way to 16 points in the period, and
Louisiana-Lafayette (2-5) managed only two 3-pointers.

	   The Rajun' Cajuns, playing for the first time in a week,
committed 15 turnovers in the opening half and finally broke their
two-point skid when Richey's simple 13-footer rattled in with 17:42
remaining in the game.

	   Hall, in his first season as Cajuns' coach, tried early to keep
the dam from breaking, calling two timeouts in the first four
minutes. But South Carolina could not be slowed.

	   Penn's inside shot made it 17-2 with 16:01 to go. Three minutes
later, Morrone had her fourth 3-pointer and Penn another basket and
the lead was 24-5.

	   Louisiana-Lafayette closed things to 24-11 on Charlotte Green's
3-pointer with 9:29 left in the half and looked like it might
recover from the South Carolina's opening run.

	   "I thought we were going to be OK after that,'' Hall said.
"But then they scored something like the next 16 points.''

	   Penn began the Gamecocks' next run with two more field goals and
Cristina Ciocan a 3-pointer to extend the margin and regain
momentum.

	   Ciocan's jumper with 3.2 seconds left gave the Gamecocks a 40-11
lead heading to the locker room.

	   "They didn't get a basket?'' asked Morrone, who finished with
15 points. She scanned the score sheet. "I see that now,'' she
said, smiling as she looked at Walvius.

	   With the game out of hand, the biggest cheer of the first half
may have come when the Gamecocks' 6-foot-4 freshman Olga Gritsaeva,
a 17-year-old Russian eligible for her first game, leaped to knock
free a ball that got stuck between the rim and the backboard.

	   It didn't go much better for the Cajuns in the second half as
South Carolina built its lead to 66-31 after back-to-back baskets
by Gritsaeva.

	   Green, Louisiana-Lafayette's top scorer coming in at 14.3 points
a game, was 2-of-17 for 8 points.

	   "We need to do this every game,'' Morrone said. "That needs to
be our focus. We did a good job in the first half and that needs to
be what we do for 40 minutes, every game.''

	   The schedule gets much tougher on Friday night with a game
against No. 13 North Carolina.

	   "I like the players we have, I like the talent that we have,''
Walvius said. But "I don't know. We've got to play a little more
consistent than we have in the last couple of days.''
